# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: e-an-zen
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] Knopf was a member of the National Academy of Sciences and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] He served as president of the Geological Society of America in 1944 and received its Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] His second wife, Eleanora Knopf, was a notable geologist and frequent collaborator.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] Knopf was born December 2, 1882, in San Francisco, California, to German American immigrants.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] He grew up with his family on a ranch near Woodside, California.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] Knopf entered the University of California, Berkeley, where he became a student of petrology under Andrew Lawson.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] He earned a Bachelor of Science degree in mining geology in 1904 and a Master of Science degree in 1905.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] That same year he spent the first of six summers surveying the mineral deposits of Alaska for the United States Geological Survey (USGS).
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] In 1906 he moved to Washington, D.C., to work for the USGS full-time.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] The Alaskan Division, of which Knopf was one of about a dozen members, was considered the best geologic group in the USGS at that time.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] Knopf's work on tin deposits in the Seward Peninsula became the basis of the dissertation for his Ph.D., which he received from Berkeley in 1909.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] In Alaska he also discovered the minerals hulsite and paigeite.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] In 1911 Knopf was promoted from assistant geologist to geologist.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] Over the next nine years he undertook a series of field projects for the USGS, beginning with the mining district in Montana that includes the Boulder Batholith and continuing to other western states including Nevada and California.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] In the latter state he surveyed the Gold Country.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] After discovering that universities on the eastern seaboard were paying about double the USGS salaries, Knopf left the USGS for a teaching position, and a number of his colleagues followed suit.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale University in January 1920.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] He encouraged students to work with the USGS as he had done; this helped mitigate the agency's brain drain following the departures.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale as an associate professor but was promoted to full professor in 1923.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] He was named the Silliman Professor of Geology in 1937 and a Sterling Professor in 1938.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] He was director of graduate studies from 1933 until his retirement from Yale in 1951.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] Upon retiring he returned to his native Woodside, California, settling not far from his family's old ranch.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] There he accepted a visiting appointment at the Stanford University School of Earth Sciences, where he remained until his death in 1966.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] Knopf's field work continued through his Yale and Stanford appointments, again with a focus on western states.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] He continued his work in the Boulder Batholith and investigated intrusive igneous rock bodies in the Spanish Peaks in Colorado.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] He also contributed to the emerging field of geochronology, putting lower bounds of 2 billion years and later 4.5 billion years on the age of the Earth.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] Knopf was elected to the National Academy of Sciences in 1931.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] He was also a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences and of the Geological Society of America.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] He was president of the Geological Society of America in 1944, and he received the Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] In 1937 he was vice president of the Society of Economic Geologists.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] In 1908 Knopf married Agnes Burchard Dillon.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] They had three daughters and one son, though one of the daughters died in infancy.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] Agnes died in 1918 in that year's flu pandemic.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] In June 1920, Knopf married fellow USGS geologist Eleanora Frances Bliss, who as Eleanora Knopf became a frequent collaborator and travel companion.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] When Adolph moved to Yale, which did not then hire women, Eleanora worked out of Adolph's office, teaching private classes and still accepting USGS assignments.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] When they moved to California, Stanford hired her as a research associate.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] Knopf died November 23, 1966, in Palo Alto, California.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] In his will he endowed a chaired professorship at Yale.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] The sitting Adolph Knopf Professor of Petrology is Shun-ichiro Karato.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] Adolph and Eleanora Knopf also endowed a graduate fellowship in petrology at Stanford.
[src:e-an-zen/adolph-knopf] Mount Adolph Knopf in Juneau Borough, Alaska is named after him.
[src:e-an-zen/albert-w-bally] Bally started his career at Shell Oil Company, retiring as Chief Geologist after 27 years in 1981.
[src:e-an-zen/albert-w-bally] After retirement, he joined Rice University as chair of the Department of Geology and Geophysics.
[src:e-an-zen/albert-w-bally] He remained active in the department until his death in 2019.
[src:e-an-zen/albert-w-bally] In 1988, Bally was elected President of the Geological Society of America.
[src:e-an-zen/alexander-winchell] Winchell graduated from the Wesleyan University of Middletown, Connecticut, in 1847.
[src:e-an-zen/alexander-winchell] He then taught at Pennington Male Seminary of New Jersey, Amenia Seminary of New York (where he had previously been a student), an academy in Newbern, Alabama, and the Mesopotamia Female Seminary of Eutaw, the last of which was founded by him.
[src:e-an-zen/alexander-winchell] He became president of the Masonic University at Selma, Alabama, in 1853.
[src:e-an-zen/alexander-winchell] He was elected as a member of the American Philosophical Society in 1865.
[src:e-an-zen/alexander-winchell] In 1854 Winchell entered the service of the University of Michigan as professor of physics and civil engineering.
[src:e-an-zen/alexander-winchell] Eventually he became professor of geology and paleontology at Michigan.
[src:e-an-zen/alexander-winchell] In 1859, Winchell was appointed as State Geologist of Michigan for the newly formed second geological survey of the state.
[src:e-an-zen/alexander-winchell] He held the post until 1863 when the state did not appropriate funding to continue the survey.
[src:e-an-zen/alexander-winchell] The survey was resumed in 1869, and Winchell was reappointed in April.
[src:e-an-zen/alexander-winchell] Owing to conflicting opinions between Winchell and his superiors, he resigned in 1871.
[src:e-an-zen/alexander-winchell] In 1863 Winchell took up a lease on a cotton plantation near Vicksburg, Mississippi, under a plan devised by Gen.
[src:e-an-zen/alexander-winchell] Lorenzo Thomas to lease plantations along the Mississippi River to loyal men from the North, who would hire black laborers on terms prescribed by the army.
[src:e-an-zen/alexander-winchell] Winchell organized the Ann Arbor Cotton Company and sold stock to the university's president, whereupon he received a leave of absence to engage in cotton planting.
[src:e-an-zen/alexander-winchell] General Thomas set wages at a low level ($7 per month for men, $5 for women, minus the cost of medical attention and clothing).
[src:e-an-zen/alexander-winchell] Even then, many lessees defrauded the freedmen of their earnings.
[src:e-an-zen/alexander-winchell] In the winter of 1863–64, the Treasury Department briefly assumed control of the Mississippi Valley labor system, mandated a substantial increase in black wages, and contemplated leasing the plantations directly to the freedmen.
[src:e-an-zen/alexander-winchell] The venture brought him only problems, and after he returned to Michigan in 1864, his brother Martin, who was managing the plantation, was killed by guerrillas.
[src:e-an-zen/alexander-winchell] In 1872, he was appointed chancellor of Syracuse University.
[src:e-an-zen/alexander-winchell] The depression of 1873 affected both his personal finances and those of Syracuse, and these troubles led him to resign this position in 1874.
[src:e-an-zen/alexander-winchell] In 1875, he worked as a professor of geology and zoology at Vanderbilt University.
[src:e-an-zen/alexander-winchell] There, his views on evolution, as expressed in his book *Adamites and Preadamites: or, A Popular Discussion* (1878), were not acceptable to the University administration because they diverged from Biblical teaching.
[src:e-an-zen/alexander-winchell] Today the views on the "inferiority of the Negro" (quote from his 1878 book) would probably have been the focus of controversy.
[src:e-an-zen/alexander-winchell] In any case, he was obligated to resign in 1878.
[src:e-an-zen/alexander-winchell] In 1888, he co-founded the Geological Society of America in Ithaca, New York along with John J.
[src:e-an-zen/alexander-winchell] He served as the 3rd president of GSA in 1891.
[src:e-an-zen/alexander-winchell] He then returned to the University of Michigan, where he was professor of geology and paleontology.
[src:e-an-zen/alexander-winchell] His work in geology was not so significant as his teaching and popular lectures and writing in this field.
[src:e-an-zen/alexander-winchell] He was much concerned with reconciling science and religion.
[src:e-an-zen/alexander-winchell] He was an advocate of theistic evolution.
[src:e-an-zen/alexander-winchell] The fish **Clear chub** *Hybopsis winchelli* (Girard, 1856) is named after him.
[src:e-an-zen/alexander-winchell] The University of Michigan named a wing of the West Quad dormitory after Winchell, and Ann Arbor honored him with Winchell Park, a neighborhood park on the city's east side.
[src:e-an-zen/alexander-winchell] Winchell's name was removed from the dormitory in 2018, and the park was renamed after former Ann Arbor Public Schools board president Harold J.
[src:e-an-zen/alexander-winchell] In removing Winchell's name, the university described his *Preadamites* as an "unambiguously racist" work.
[src:e-an-zen/alfred-church-lane] Lane was educated at Harvard University and received his A.B. degree in 1883.
[src:e-an-zen/alfred-church-lane] Between 1883 and 1885 he taught mathematics at Harvard, then studied at the University of Heidelberg until 1887 before returning to Harvard to earn his Ph.D. in 1888.
[src:e-an-zen/alfred-church-lane] The following year he joined the Michigan State Geologic Survey as a petrographer, and he remained in that post into 1892 while also serving as an instructor at the Michigan College of Mines.
[src:e-an-zen/alfred-church-lane] He became assistant state geologist for Michigan in 1892, and from 1899 to 1909 he was the state geologist.
[src:e-an-zen/alfred-church-lane] Finally, he joined Tufts College in 1892, becoming the Pearson professor of geology and mineralogy.
[src:e-an-zen/alfred-church-lane] He retired from the college in 1936 as professor emeritus.
[src:e-an-zen/alfred-church-lane] While at Tufts, he served as vice president of the AAAS Division of Geology in 1907.
[src:e-an-zen/alfred-church-lane] He received an honorary D.Sc. from Tufts in 1913.
[src:e-an-zen/alfred-church-lane] From 1922 and 1946 he was chairman for the Committee on the Measurement of Geologic Time for the National Research Council.
[src:e-an-zen/alfred-church-lane] He served as a member of the Board of Visitors at Harvard Observatory in 1924.
[src:e-an-zen/alfred-church-lane] Alfred Lane was appointed as consultant of science to the Library of Congress in 1929; the first person to hold that post.
[src:e-an-zen/alfred-church-lane] In 1931, he was president of the Geological Society of America.
[src:e-an-zen/alfred-church-lane] He was awarded the Ballou Medal by Tufts College in 1940 for "distinguished service to education and the nation".
[src:e-an-zen/alfred-church-lane] During his career, he authored 1,087 publications.
[src:e-an-zen/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The **American Academy of Arts and Sciences** (**The Academy**) is one of the oldest learned societies in the United States.
[src:e-an-zen/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It was founded in 1780 during the American Revolution by John Adams, John Hancock, James Bowdoin, Andrew Oliver, and other Founding Fathers of the United States.
[src:e-an-zen/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It is headquartered in Cambridge, Massachusetts.
[src:e-an-zen/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Membership in the academy is achieved through a nominating petition, review, and election process.
[src:e-an-zen/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The academy's quarterly journal, *Dædalus*, is published by the MIT Press on behalf of the academy, and has been open-access since January 2021.
[src:e-an-zen/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The academy also conducts multidisciplinary public policy research.
[src:e-an-zen/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Patton has served as President of the Academy since January 2025.
[src:e-an-zen/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The first class of new members, chosen by the Academy in 1781, included Benjamin Franklin and George Washington as well as several international honorary members.
[src:e-an-zen/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The initial volume of Academy *Memoirs* appeared in 1785, and the *Proceedings* followed in 1846.
[src:e-an-zen/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the 1950s, the Academy launched its journal *Daedalus*, reflecting its commitment to a broader intellectual and socially-oriented program.
[src:e-an-zen/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Since the second half of the twentieth century, independent research has become a central focus of the Academy.
[src:e-an-zen/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the late 1950s, arms control emerged as one of its signature concerns.
[src:e-an-zen/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The Academy also served as the catalyst in establishing the National Humanities Center in North Carolina.
[src:e-an-zen/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the late 1990s, the Academy developed a new strategic plan, focusing on four major areas: science, technology, and global security; social policy and education; humanities and culture; and education.
[src:e-an-zen/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In 2002, the Academy established a visiting scholars program in association with Harvard University.
[src:e-an-zen/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] More than 75 academic institutions from across the country have become Affiliates of the Academy to support this program and other Academy initiatives.
[src:e-an-zen/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The Academy has sponsored a number of awards and prizes, throughout its history and has offered opportunities for fellowships and visiting scholars at the Academy.
[src:e-an-zen/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In July 2013, *The Boston Globe* exposed then president Leslie Berlowitz for falsifying her credentials, faking a doctorate, and consistently mistreating her staff.
[src:e-an-zen/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It is modeled on the Science and Engineering Indicators, published biennially by the National Science Board as required by Congress.
[src:e-an-zen/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Ever since the founding of the Academy, its members have been nominated and elected by peers.
[src:e-an-zen/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Members of the Academy included not only scientists and scholars, but also writers and artists as well as representatives from the full range of professions and public life.
[src:e-an-zen/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Throughout the Academy's history, more than 10,000 fellows have been elected.
[src:e-an-zen/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Astronomer Maria Mitchell was the first woman elected to the Academy, in 1848.
[src:e-an-zen/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The current membership encompasses over 5,700 members based across the United States and around the world.
[src:e-an-zen/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Academy members include more than 250 Nobel laureates and more than 60 Pulitzer Prize winners.
[src:e-an-zen/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Of the Academy's 14,343 members since 1780, 1,406 are or have been affiliated with Harvard University, 611 with the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, 433 with Yale University, 425 with the University of California, Berkeley, and 404 with Stanford University.
[src:e-an-zen/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The following table includes those institutions affiliated with 300 or more members.
[src:e-an-zen/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] † Excludes members affiliated exclusively with associated national laboratories.
[src:e-an-zen/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] As of 2023, membership is divided into five classes and thirty specialties.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] AAAS was the first permanent organization established to promote science and engineering nationally and to represent the interests of American researchers from across all scientific fields.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] It is the world's largest general scientific society, with over 120,000 members, and is the publisher of the well-known scientific journal *Science*.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The American Association for the Advancement of Science was created on September 20, 1848, at the Academy of Natural Sciences in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] According to the first constitution which was agreed to at the September 20 meeting, the goal of the society was to promote scientific dialogue in order to allow for greater scientific collaboration.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] By doing so, the association aimed to use resources to conduct science with increased efficiency and allow for scientific progress at a greater rate.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The association also sought to increase the resources available to the scientific community through active advocacy of science.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] There were only 78 members when the AAAS was formed.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] As a member of the new scientific body, Matthew Fontaine Maury, USN was one of those who attended the first 1848 meeting.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] At a meeting held on Friday afternoon, September 22, 1848, Redfield presided, and Matthew Fontaine Maury gave a full scientific report on his *Wind and Current Charts*.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Maury stated that hundreds of ship navigators were now sending abstract logs of their voyages to the United States Naval Observatory.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] He added, "Never before was such a corps of observers known." But, he pointed out to his fellow scientists, his critical need was for more "simultaneous observations".
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] "The work," Maury stated, "is not exclusively for the benefit of any nation or age".
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Coffin of Easton, Pennsylvania, and Professor Stephen Alexander of Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] This was scientific cooperation, and Maury went back to Washington with great hopes for the future.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In 1850, the first female members were accepted: astronomer Maria Mitchell and entomologist Margaretta Morris.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Science educator Almira Hart Lincoln Phelps was elected in 1859.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] By 1860, membership increased to over 2,000.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Although the AAAS became dormant during the American Civil War (their August 1861 meeting in Nashville, Tennessee, was postponed indefinitely after the outbreak of the first major engagement of the war at Bull Run), the association recovered after the end of the hostilities.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In 1866, Frederick Barnard presided over the first meeting of the resurrected AAAS at a meeting in New York City.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Following the revival of the AAAS, the group had considerable growth.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The AAAS permitted all people, regardless of scientific credentials, to join.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The AAAS did, however, institute a policy of granting the title of "Fellow of the AAAS" to well-respected scientists within the organization.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Also, the reputation of the AAAS was somewhat tarnished, because its 3rd president Alexander Dallas Bache used the Society as a lobbying tool for his agency, the US Coast Survey.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Several prominent scientists lost interest in the AAAS, and the society's influence declined.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The next turning point in the AAAS history was the partnership with journal *Science*, which became the society's official publication in 1900, and provided the AAAS with some revenue through subscription and advertising.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The AAAS become the sole owner of *Science* in 1946.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Another important event for the society was the establishment of its Congressional Fellowship program in 1973, which was kick-started by a US$10,000 donation from William T.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Leshner, AAAS CEO from 2001 until 2015, published many op-ed articles discussing how many people integrate science and religion in their lives.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] He has opposed the insertion of non-scientific content, such as creationism or intelligent design, into the scientific curriculum of schools.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In February 2007, the AAAS used satellite images to document human rights abuses in Burma.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The next year, AAAS launched the Center for Science Diplomacy to advance both science and the broader relationships among partner countries, by promoting science diplomacy and international scientific cooperation.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In 2012, AAAS published op-eds, held events on Capitol Hill and released analyses of the U.S. federal research-and-development budget, to warn that a budget sequestration would have severe consequences for scientific progress.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] AAAS covers various areas of sciences and engineering.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] It has 24 sections, each with a committee and its chair.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] These committees are also entrusted with the annual evaluation and selection of Fellows.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The most recent Constitution of the AAAS, enacted on January 1, 1973, establishes that the governance of the AAAS is accomplished through four entities: a President, a group of administrative officers, a Council, and a board of directors.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Individuals elected to the presidency of the AAAS hold a three-year term in a unique way.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The first year is spent as president-elect, the second as president and the third as chairperson of the board of directors.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In accordance with the convention followed by the AAAS, presidents are referenced by the year in which they left office.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Geraldine Richmond is the president of AAAS for 2015–16; Phillip Sharp is the board chair; and Barbara A.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Each took office on the last day of the 2015 AAAS Annual Meeting in February 2015.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] On the last day of the 2016 AAAS Annual Meeting, February 15, 2016, Richmond will become the chair, Schaal will become the president, and a new president-elect will take office.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Past presidents of AAAS have included some of the most important scientific figures of their time.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Among them: explorer and geologist John Wesley Powell (1888); astronomer and physicist Edward Charles Pickering (1912); anthropologist Margaret Mead (1975); and biologist Stephen Jay Gould (2000).
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] There are three classifications of high-level administrative officials that execute the basic, daily functions of the AAAS.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] These are the executive officer, the treasurer and then each of the AAAS's section secretaries.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The current CEO of AAAS and executive publisher of *Science* magazine is Sudip Parikh.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The current Editor in Chief of Science magazine is Holden Thorp.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The AAAS has 24 "sections" with each section being responsible for a particular concern of the AAAS.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] AAAS affiliates include 262 societies and academies of science, serving more than 10 million members, from the Acoustical Society of America to the Wildlife Society, as well as non-mainstream groups like the Parapsychological Association.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The council is composed of the members of the Board of Directors, the retiring section chairmen, elected delegates and affiliated foreign council members.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Among the elected delegates there are always at least two members from the National Academy of Sciences and one from each region of the country.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The President of the AAAS serves as the Chairperson of the council.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Members serve the council for a term of three years.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The council meets annually to discuss matters of importance to the AAAS.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] They have the power to review all activities of the Association, elect new fellows, adopt resolutions, propose amendments to the Association's constitution and bylaws, create new scientific sections, and organize and aid local chapters of the AAAS.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The Council recently has new additions to it from different sections which include many youngsters as well.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] John Kerry of Chicago is the youngest American in the council and Akhil Ennamsetty of India is the youngest foreign council member.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The board of directors is composed of a chairperson, the president, and the president-elect along with eight elected directors, the executive officer of the association and up to two additional directors appointed by elected officers.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Members serve a four-year term except for directors appointed by elected officers, who serve three-year terms.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The current chairman is Gerald Fink, Margaret and Herman Sokol Professor at Whitehead Institute, MIT.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Fink will serve in the post until the end of the 2016 AAAS Annual Meeting, 15 February 2016.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The board of directors has a variety of powers and responsibilities.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] It is charged with the administration of all association funds, publication of a budget, appointment of administrators, proposition of amendments, and determining the time and place of meetings of the national association.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The board may also speak publicly on behalf of the association.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The board must also regularly correspond with the council to discuss their actions.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The AAAS council elects every year, its members who are distinguished scientifically, to the grade of fellow (**FAAAS**).
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Election to AAAS is an honor bestowed by their peers and elected fellows are presented with a certificate and rosette pin.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Formal meetings of the AAAS are numbered consecutively, starting with the first meeting in 1848.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Meetings were not held 1861–1865 during the American Civil War, and also 1942–1943 during World War II.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Since 1946, one meeting has occurred annually, now customarily in February.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Each year, the AAAS gives out a number of honorary awards, most of which focus on science communication, journalism, and outreach – sometimes in partnership with other organizations.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The awards recognize "scientists, journalists, and public servants for significant contributions to science and to the public's understanding of science".
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The awards are presented each year at the association's annual meeting.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] These policy fellows spend one or two years working for the executive (130 positions), legislative (5 positions) or judicial (1 position) branches.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The society's flagship publication is *Science*, a weekly interdisciplinary scientific journal.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Other peer-reviewed journals published by the AAAS in the "*Science* family of journals" are *Science Signaling*, *Science Translational Medicine*, *Science Immunology*, *Science Robotics* and the interdisciplinary *Science Advances*.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] They also publish the non-peer-reviewed *Science & Diplomacy*.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] The society previously published the review journal *Science Books & Films* (SB&F).
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] AAAS also publishes on behalf of other organizations through the Science Partner Journals (SPJ) program, with a focus on online-only open access journals.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] SciLine is a philanthropically funded and editorially independent service for journalists and scientists.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Its launch was announced in an October 27, 2017 article in Science by founding director Rick Weiss, former communications chief at the White House Office of Science and Technology Policy and science reporter at the Washington Post.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Its stated mission is to increase the amount and quality of research-backed evidence in news stories by connecting U.S. journalists to scientists and to validated scientific information.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Reporters in the United States can access SciLine's services, which include expert-matching, general media briefings, expert quote sheets, and quick fact sheets.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] As of July 2021, SciLine had fulfilled approximately 2,000 requests from 650 journalists through its expert-matching service.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] SciLine's financial supporters include the Quadrivium Foundation, the Chan Zuckerberg Initiative, the John S. and James L.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Knight Foundation, the Rita Allen Foundation, and the Heinz Endowments.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In 1996, AAAS launched the **EurekAlert!** website, an editorially independent nonprofit news release distribution service covering all areas of science, medicine and technology.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] EurekAlert! provides news in English, Spanish, French, German, Portuguese, Japanese, and, from 2007, in Chinese.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Working staff journalists and freelancers who meet eligibility guidelines can access the latest studies before publication and obtain embargoed information in compliance with the U.S.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] Securities and Exchange Commission's Regulation Fair Disclosure policy.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] By early 2018, more than 14,000 reporters from more than 90 countries have registered for free access to embargoed materials.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] More than 5,000 active public information officers from 2,300 universities, academic journals, government agencies, and medical centers are credentialed to provide new releases to reporters and the public through the system.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] In 1998, European science organizations countered Eurekalert! with a press release distribution service AlphaGalileo.
[src:e-an-zen/american-association-for-the-advancement-of-science] EurekAlert! has fallen under criticism for lack of press release standards and for generating churnalism.
[src:e-an-zen/american-geological-institute] The **American Geosciences Institute** (**AGI**) is a nonprofit federation of about 50 geoscientific and professional organizations that represents geologists, geophysicists, and other earth scientists.
[src:e-an-zen/american-geological-institute] The organization's offices are in Alexandria, Virginia.
[src:e-an-zen/american-geological-institute] The name of the organization was changed from the **American Geological Institute** on October 1, 2011.
[src:e-an-zen/american-geological-institute] Since 1966, AGI has produced GeoRef, a literature database for those studying the earth sciences.
[src:e-an-zen/american-geological-institute] AGI operates the Center for Geosciences and Society.
[src:e-an-zen/american-geological-institute] AGI's monthly magazine *Geotimes* became *EARTH Magazine* on September 1, 2008, with an increased focus on public communication of geoscience research.
[src:e-an-zen/american-geological-institute] In April 2019, *EARTH Magazine* suspended publication and was folded into *Nautilus Quarterly*.
[src:e-an-zen/american-geological-institute] The stated mission of AGI is to "represent and serve the geoscience community by providing collaborative leadership and information to connect Earth, science, and people".
[src:e-an-zen/american-geological-institute] GeoRef offers a variety of specialized databases for researchers, educators, and students in specific areas of geoscience.
[src:e-an-zen/american-geological-institute] AGI offers lessons and curricula designed for teachers of Earth sciences in schools (K-12).
[src:e-an-zen/american-geological-institute] These educational resources are created in partnership with geological organizations whose work is related to Earth science concepts.
[src:e-an-zen/american-geological-institute] Every year in the second full week of October, AGI runs Earth Science Week, to promote understanding of Earth science and stewardship of the planet.
[src:e-an-zen/american-geological-institute] The Geological Society of America (GSA) and the National Cooperative Geological Mapping Program of the U.S.
[src:e-an-zen/american-geological-institute] Geological Survey hold the Annual Best Student Geologic Map Competition to bring together student geologic mappers from around the world.
[src:e-an-zen/e-an-zen] **E-An Zen** (Chinese: 任以安; pinyin: *Rén Yǐ'ān*) was born in Peking, China, May 31, 1928, and came to the U.S. in 1946.
[src:e-an-zen/e-an-zen] He became a citizen in 1963 and from 1990 was an adjunct professor at the University of Maryland.
[src:e-an-zen/e-an-zen] He died on March 29, 2014, at the age of 85.
[src:e-an-zen/e-an-zen] He was a member of the Geological Society of Washington (Pres.
[src:e-an-zen/e-an-zen] 1973), the National Academy of Sciences, and the Mineralogical Association of Canada.
[src:e-an-zen/e-an-zen] Zen was active in programs to bring geological knowledge to the general public.
[src:e-an-zen/e-an-zen] Received A.B from Cornell University in 1951, M.A from Harvard University in 1952, and PhD from Harvard University in 1955.
[src:e-an-zen/e-an-zen] Research fellow at Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution, 1955–56; and a research associate, 1956–58.
[src:e-an-zen/e-an-zen] From 1958 to 1959 he was a visiting assistant professor at the University of North Carolina.
[src:e-an-zen/e-an-zen] Geological Survey from 1959 to 1980, and a Research geologist, 1980–89.
[src:e-an-zen/e-an-zen] Visiting associate professor at the California Institute of Technology, 1962; Crosby Visiting Professor, Massachusetts Institute of Technology, 1973; Harry Hess Senior Visiting Fellow, Princeton University, 1981; and Visiting Fellow, Australian National University, 1991.
[src:e-an-zen/e-an-zen] Zen worked primarily in the northern Appalachians, especially on paleogeographic reconstructions and the origins of exotic terranes in New England.
[src:e-an-zen/e-an-zen] Day Medal, Geological Society of America, 1986; Roebling Medal, Mineralogical Society of America, 1991; John Coke Medal, Geological Society of London, 1992; and the Distinguished Service Medal, U.S.
[src:e-an-zen/e-an-zen] He was also honored for outstanding contributions to public understanding of geology (American Geological Institute, 1994) and with the Thomas Jefferson Medal, Virginia Museum of Natural History, 1995.
